Информация на РУССКОМ языке находится ЗДЕСЬFor orders of 6 books or more, to make a customized order, or if you prefer to make a contribution without ordering a book, please contact me directly at barzuworld@gmail.com.To pay by PayPal option, please, contact me at barzuworld@gmail.comMy website: https://marinaabrams.com/ 
Family reading time;
Reading in Russian or English for bilingual families;
A gift (kids love big books);
Reading at daycare. Some daycares allow parents to come and read books or organize activities as a way to celebrate their child's birthday. Our book is a perfect choice for that!
Demonstration at the school's International Day;
School project on Central Asia;
Theatrical performance at local community center, studio, or art school.    

Hardcover and good quality paper.
The size of the book will be 12x11 inches/31x28cm (Kids love huge books!).
 Large font for easy reading.
34 beautiful illustrations (double-page spread) by Farrukh Negmatzade.
96 pages.
"A long, long time ago, in a place where great roads crossed, stood the City of Blue Domes. The city was full of narrow, winding streets and intricate mosaics on the walls of its high towers. Many different kinds of people lived there - traders and craftsmen, musicians and dancers, the rich and the poor - and everyone spoke two or three languages so they could understand one another and live together in peace and harmony.The city was famous for its bazaars – marketplaces, where everybody sold and bought goods. Oh, and what you could not find there, among the stalls! Sweet and juicy fruits, crisp vegetables, clay pots, expensive jewelry, boots, the finest, dyed silks, handmade carpets, rare books – everything your heart could desire!""And so, one day a merchant named Fayeez departed with his caravan to far-off Hindustan, the land of rich maharajas, from where he always brought spices and medicines, pearls, precious stones and fabulous fabrics. For several months he would travel overland, trudging through the deserts and hills with his caravan of camels, his faithful helpers, and brave horsemen. Arriving in the City of the Sun, in the land of Marwar, Fayeez immediately went to the fortress, which towered over a high cliff of red rock, and where the local ruler, maharaja Sardar, was always ready to welcome merchants."Children 3 - 12 years old. My goal has been to make this book interesting and understandable not only for children of all ages, but also for their parents. Thus, the book is divided into several parts: the story itself, which includes history and fable; folkloric narrative on how people really live; and an educational section at the end of the story for parents to discuss with their children."The servants opened the chest and withdrew from it round loaves of bread that Fayeez brought from the City of Blue Domes. Over the six months that they sat in the chest, their crusts had become stale and hard.Taking them into his hands, the maharaja roared with displeasure: “What is this? What are these rocks you have brought me, Merchant Fayeez?”“This is bread from my city,” said Fayeez with pride. “There is no such bread anywhere in the world!”“Are you playing a trick on me?!” the Maharaja growled, his brow knit in anger. “On such bread as this you would have me break my teeth!”“Do not be angry, your Highness. For these are loaves of the most unusual bread.”The main incentive for creating this book was the birth of my children. All parents want to share our sense of the world with our children, and instill in them a love for those things that we love, ourselves. And what do I love? To read and to travel! To learn about other cultures, about the history of far-off lands, and to make new friends.My life is closely tied to Central Asia. I was born and spent my childhood in a small Uighur town on the border between Kazakhstan and China. My early years were much like Barzu’s - many women there baked bread in special clay ovens, called tanoors; my sister and I played with real clay from the ground and not plasticine; donkeys grazed through the streets; and fruits and berries ripened on the trees in our and our neighbors’ yards. Much later, after I had received my graduate degree, I spent a year in Tajikistan and that country, with its magnificent mountains and welcoming culture, has stayed in my heart ever since. I gained many good friends there, who remain so to this day.I was surprised to find that there are very few books for children on Central Asia, in particular for pre-school children. After all, Central Asia is a region with over 100 ethnic groups, the land of the Great Silk Road, where Alexander the Great left his footprints, the old empires of Genghis Khan and Tamerlane!One day some time ago, my husband brought several souvenir mugs back from a business trip to Tajikistan, which were decorated with illustrations by our friend, the artist Farrukh Negmatzade. The images on the mugs were so compelling that I immediately began to imagine stories for each of them, which I told to my children. Thus, was born the idea to create a series of books about the Tajik boy, Barzu. My hope is that, through these books, young readers will become familiar not just with the culture of the Tajik people, but gradually learn about many other nationalities from Central Asia.I have been working for the past year on this rather unique book. During this time, I barraged my friends in Tajikistan and Uzbekistan with hundreds of questions, corresponded with experts and historians, flew to the region in person and personally visited tanoor workshops, and read through a lot of historical and ethnographic literature.And, of course, I consider it a privilege that, despite all the demands on his time, the great Farrukh-Aka (Uncle Farrukh) agreed to illustrate this book!  Who else could portray all the charm of Tajik life with such poignancy and detail, except an artist living and breathing his native, Tajik land? Irina from Boston, mother of two boys Petya (age 6) and Misha (age 4)My kids love to look in detail at the pictures and match them with the story and ask questions. We all liked the book. We had to find Tajikistan on the globe. The kids were fascinated with the new words like "tanoor" and "kishlak," and names of people that do not sound like what they are used to. They were curious about tanoor, the peculiar way it looks and the way the dough is placed inside of it to make bread. The big hit was the chapter “Orange Roofs.” My boys were surprised to learn that people dry apricots on the roof under the sun and that they turn into "kuraga" which I often pack for them as a snack. They also liked the way Barzu solved the problem for the girls who did not know how to share the strings.As a parent I appreciated many opportunities to expand beyond the story. Like trying to find the country on the map. Telling about the different lifestyle people have. When they have to be more self reliant and closer to nature, like making ovens and baking bread from scratch. It is a big difference with our hectic lives and frozen food from supermarket. We spread dried apricots on the table and imagined the orange roofs of the houses in kishlak.Natalia Mironova, currently lives in CaliforniaThe story flows like an oriental pattern. Very simple language creates vivid and memorable images of mountains, the blue sky, ancient traditions, an old sun-lit city with roofs covered by orange apricots. We enter the wonderful world of a clever Tajik boy, hardworking and curious, who travels by bicycle to his grandmother. Together with him we discover his grandmother's secrets and the eternal wisdom of Central Asian life and folklore. This is a very good book. As the grandmother of three grandchildren, I am glad of this book’s appearance and, undoubtedly, the emergence of a new author.Marina Abrams – Author of “Orange and Blue: The World of Barzu” and the pending book series,The World of Barzu; project director and founder of “Barzu World.” I was born and raised in Kazakhstan. I consider my high-school years the most formative for my writing skills, where I studied Russian language and literature at Specialized School #134, in Almaty. I then enrolled into the Translation-Interpretation Department at the Abylaikhan Kazakh State University of International Relations and World Languages, where in addition to English, I studied Chinese and Spanish. I received my M.A. in International Policy Studies at Monterey Institute of International Studies (now the Middlebury Institute of International Studies at Monterey) in California.Farrukh Negmatzade – Illustrator of “Orange and Blue: The World of Barzu;” and a well-known, contemporary artist of Tajikistan. We met in 2005, when I lived in Dushanbe, Tajikistan. In fact, we were neighbors and have become very good friends ever since. He is the father of three children and four grandchildren. Farrukh Negmatzade graduated from Moscow Art School under the Academy of Arts of USSR, and in 1982 graduated from Moscow Surikov State Art Institute. More information about Farrukh Negmat-Zade at www.http://farrukhnegmatzade.com/Joshua Abrams – translator from Russian into English. My husband, a wonderful father to my children, and a talented writer. Joshua studied Russian in St Petersburg, was a Peace Corps Volunteer in Kazakhstan, and has lived and worked in most of the countries of the former Soviet Union. He’s a graduate of Bard College (BA) and Indiana University (MPA/MA) and has also published his own articles and stories. Most importantly, my husband was the one who brought me to Tajikistan! Jonah Abrams (Age 5) and Annabelle Abrams (Age 2). My children, they are my first audience and contributors into my every day creative process. And they are waiting for this book impatientlyNatalia Kuzmina – Russian language copy editor. Natalia is a graduate of the Philology Department at Novosibirsk State University, Russia. From 1993 to 1996 Natalia and I studied together in the Philology Group at Specialized High School #134 in Almaty, Kazakhstan. And now, 20 years later we are happy to work together in this project. Thanks to her, all comas will be in the right place. Most important, Natalia is a mother of three wonderful boys - Maxim (8 y.o.), Alexander (3 y.o.) and Nicholas (18 months).AUGUST-SEPTEMBER-OCTOBER: Prepare E-color book. Send out E-color books by e-mail and other rewards, if they were not ordered together with the book. Finalize electronic version of the hardcover book “Orange and Blue: The World of Barzu” for printing. Print the hardcover book.NOVEMBER: Ship hardcover books and other rewards. The book is in your hands for wonderful fall reading at home and at school!NOVEMBER: Start delivering the Eastern Tale reward.Due to our successful campaign on Kickstarter thousands of children around the world will soon read the first book about Barzu. I also have two more books in line for final editing and illustration, which will make them a series called The World of Barzu.OUR AMAZING BUTTON PINS!Photo by Yuri ShurmistovPhoto by Yuri ShurmistovPhoto by Yuri Shurmistov OUR UNIQUE GREETING CARDS!Photo by Yuri Shurmistov
